Class Subdivision

  • java.lang.Object
    • Subdivision
  • public class Subdivision
extends java.lang.Object
    A Subdivision is a collection of houses.

    Note that houses are identified by the order in which they are added (zero origin). So if I add Houses a , b and c in that order, house 0 is a , house 1 is b , and house 2 is c .

    Author:
    parks

      • list

        public java.util.ArrayList<House> list()
        Accessor to return the list of all houses in the subdivision in the order in which they were added.

        This method is part of Subdivision Step 1

        Returns:
        the list of houses in the subdivision in the order in which they were added. If the subdivision has no houses, this list will be empty. It will never be null.

      • listByBedrooms

        public java.util.ArrayList<House> listByBedrooms​(int floor,
                                                 int ceiling)
        Return a list of houses that have between the given number of bedrooms (inclusive).

        This is an Accessor.

        This method is part of Subdivision Step 1

        Parameters:
        floor - the minimum number of bedrooms for the houses in this list (inclusive)
        ceiling - the maximum number of bedroms for the houses in this list (inclusive)
        Returns:
        a list of houses whose number of bedrooms is floor <= numberOfBedrooms <= ceiling If there are no such houses, this list will be empty. It will not be null.

      • listByArea

        public java.util.ArrayList<House> listByArea​(double floor,
                                             double ceiling)
        Return a list of houses that are between a given number of square feet.

        This is an Accessor.

        This method is part of Subdivision Step 1

        Parameters:
        floor - the smallest house to be included in this list (inclusive)
        ceiling - the largest house to be included in this list (inclusive)
        Returns:
        a list of houses whose square footage is floor <= squareFootage <= ceiling If there are no such houses, this list will be empty. It will not be null.

      • listByPlot

        public java.util.ArrayList<House> listByPlot​(double floor,
                                             double ceiling)
        Return a list of houses whose associated plot of land is between two bounds (inclusive).

        This is an Accessor.

        This method is part of Subdivision Step 2

        Parameters:
        floor - the plot acreage for the houses in this list (inclusive)
        ceiling - the largest plot acreage for the houses in this list (inclusive)
        Returns:
        a list of houses whose plot acreage is floor <= plotSize <= ceiling If there are no such houses, this list will be empty. It will not be null.

      • sortByPlot

        public java.util.ArrayList<House> sortByPlot()
        A sorted list of all houses, ordered by plot acreage.

        This is an Accessor. It must not affect the order that the houses were added to the subdivision

        This method is part of Subdivision Step 2

        Returns:
        a list of houses ordered from the smallest plot size to the largest plot size. If the subdivision has no houses, this list will be empty. It will never be null.

      • sortByArea

        public java.util.ArrayList<House> sortByArea()
        A sorted list of all houses, ordered by the total area of the houses.

        This is an Accessor. It must not affect the order that the houses were added to the subdivision

        This method is part of Subdivision Step 2

        Returns:
        a list of houses ordered from the smallest house in square feet to the largest house. If the subdivision has no houses, this list will be empty. It will never be null.
